    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It is some time since I sent <persName ref="pe0006">M<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi> Bailey</persName> the last portion of <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0209">the Map</title>
                    </bibl> &amp; hope he is now
                    advanced so far as to be near done with his work.</p>
                <p>After the most minute search &amp; examining various Editions of <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0142">Sir David Lindsay's
                        Works</title>
                    </bibl> I cannot find these lines on <persName ref="pe0063">
                        <hi rend="underline">Cardinal Beaton's death</hi>
                    </persName> inserted in any
                    of them, these are attributed to <persName ref="pe0269">Sir David</persName> by
                        <persName ref="pe0570">M<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi> Robert
                        Wodrow</persName> in his <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0574">
                            <hi rend="underline">History of the Sufferings of the Church of
                                Scotland</hi>
                        </title>
                        <biblScope unit="volume">Vol. 2<hi rend="superscript">d.</hi>
                        </biblScope>
                        <biblScope unit="page">pag. 33</biblScope>
                    </bibl> after giving an Account of
                        <persName ref="pe0004">Archb<hi rend="superscript">p.</hi>
                        Sharp's</persName> murder he concludes with these Stanzas. <persName ref="pe0064">L<hi rend="superscript">d.</hi> Hailes</persName> writes me,
                    that his Lordship thinks these are of a more modern stile than <persName ref="pe0269">the Knight's</persName>, as must be confest is the truth, my
                    Lord says, <q>This Author was an honest &amp; laborious Man but he had not all
                        the discernment necessary for an Historian of such disordered &amp; unhappy
                        times.</q>
                </p>
                <p>I am sorry that it is out of my power to give you so small satisfaction; shall be
                    happy that your are arrived safely in <placeName ref="pl0699">London</placeName>.</p>
                <p>You will soon accept from me <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0176">the
                            History of Glasgow</title>
                    </bibl> with a plan of the Town, also <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0136">the Antiquities of
                            Stirlingshire</title>
                    </bibl> with <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0575">Edgar's Map of the County</title>
                    </bibl> so soon as
                    published, and <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0144">a Plan of the Town of
                            Dundee</title>
                    </bibl> with some Views of it just upon publishing: all
                    shall be sent to <persName ref="pe0026">M<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi>
                        White's</persName> Care for you.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I ever am Dear Sir <lb/>Your most obed<hi rend="superscript">t.</hi>
                            Serv<hi rend="superscript">t.</hi>
                    </salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0228">GPaton</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName ref="pl0696">Custom h<hi rend="superscript">o.</hi>
                        Edinburgh</placeName>
                    <lb/>1 April 1777.</dateline>
            </div>
            <div>
                <p>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Thomas Pennant Esq<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi>
                        </addrLine>
                    </address>
                </p>
            </div>
